					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Besides, I don't want the straight RGB values, since those wouldn't take hue/saturation into account. The entire GOAL of my emulator is to be as accurate as possible, and this is one part of it.</div>I see you already incorporated Blargg's new levels. I also see you're using the PAL decoder matrix with the vectors swapped; I guess you did that because you've got the chroma [] array backwards, a leftover from kev's old algorithm. If you change the chroma [] array from 210,180,... to 270,300,330,0,30... and switch the U and V vectors, you'll get proper RGB colors and the "hue" control will operate in the correct direction. If you change from the PAL decoder matrix to the NTSC decoder matrix, you'll also get the "no change" output at a hue setting of zero instead of 330. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />
<br />Also, when calculating U and V from sine and cosine, don't scale with with 1.140 and 2.032.
<br />
<br />The PAL palette is the NTSC palette with the hue "locked" at minus 15 degrees (assuming the NTSC decoder matrix). Saturation should still be adjustable.</div>

