			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Supposedly, NTSC uses YIQ and PAL uses YUV, but about half of the documents I've seen claim that NTSC switched from YIQ to YUV but don't say when - was it before or after the time of the NES?</div>NTSC never "switched", it's just that most TV sets decode using YUV instead of YIQ because you can save on some parts as you only have one coefficient for red and blue. The only difference is that decoding with YUV means you have to add 33 degrees to the hue setting. Otherwise, it's exactly the same; however, since we want the "unity" (no change) setting at a user hue setting of zero, instead of +33 degrees, we should use the YIQ decoder matrix.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The other major annoyance is that I have yet to find a SINGLE document that states how to convert the Chroma phase/amplitude (Hue/Saturation, or Tint/Color) into I/Q or U/V.</div><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">phase = colorNumber &amp; 0x0f;<br />level = colorNumber &gt;&gt; 4;<br />angle = &#40;phase - 3&#41; * 30 + userHueSetting;<br />I = sin &#40;angle * PI / 180&#41; * nesChroma &#91;level&#93; * userSaturationSetting;<br />Q = cos &#40;angle * PI / 180&#41; * nesChroma &#91;level&#93; * userSaturationSetting;<br />switch &#40;phase&#41; &#123;<br />&nbsp; case 0x00: Y = nesLuma00 &#91;level&#93;; I = 0; Q = 0; break;<br />&nbsp; case 0x0d: Y = nesLuma0d &#91;level&#93;; I = 0; Q = 0; break;<br />&nbsp; case 0x0e:<br />&nbsp; case 0x0f: Y = 0; I = 0; Q = 0; break;<br />&nbsp; default: Y = nesLuma0x &#91;level&#93;; break;<br />&#125;<br /><br />R = Y + 0.956*I + 0.621*Q;<br />G = Y - 0.272*I - 0.647*Q;<br />B = Y - 1.105*I + 1.702*Q;<br /></div>
<br />userHueSetting could be adjustable from minus 180 to plus 180, although in practice -45 to +45 are enough, with zero being the default/unity/"no change" setting. For PAL, this should be locked to -15. (Yes, the PAL hues are different from the default NTSC hues.)
<br />userSaturationSetting could be adjustable from 0.0 (black/white) to anything you like, realistically you'd have 0.0 to 2.0, with 1.0 being the default/unity/"no change" setting.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

