			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">based on the assumption that red, green, and blue were each exactly 120 degrees apart from each other, which is clearly not the case with YIQ and YUV decoding</div>Ah, ok. No, YIQ and YUV are based on that it's exactly 90 degrees from <strong>B-Y</strong> to <strong>R-Y</strong>, not from B to R. Remember that the chroma component is the color <em>difference</em> signal (to the monochrome signal, so that it's compatible to monochrome TV sets). Also, YIQ and YUV are designed to allocate more of the spectrum to green because the human eye is supposedly more sensitive to green.
<br />
<br />Of course, common implementations in consumer TV sets place B-Y and R-Y further than 90 degrees apart; I can give you a couple of matrices derived from actual Sony TV service manuals... <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
